===Etymology===
According to {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, from {{der|zh|sit}} and an area word. Externally, cognate with {{cog|bo|འགས་པ||to split; to break; to burst apart}}, {{cog|mkh-pro|*kat|*kat ~ *kaat|to cut}}, whence {{cog|km|កាត់||to cut}} and Proto-South-Bahnaric ''*kat'' ("to chop; to cut"). Within Chinese, cognate with {{och-l|害|to harm; to injure}}, and {{och-l|犗|to castrate}}, which is perhaps the r-causative of {{och-l|割}}.

On the other hand, STEDT compares it to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*d-ra-t||cut; slash}}, to which {{och-l|害|to harm; to injure}}, {{och-l|犗|to castrate}}, {{och-l|剌|to cut; perverse}} are also compared. Descended from the Proto-Sino-Tibetan root are {{cog|bo|དྲ་བ||to cut}} and {{cog|my|ရှန||wounded}}.

